title: For Sale:  COLT ~ 1911A1 U.S. ARMY Scarce COMMERCIAL/MILITARY...Mfd 1942, C&R, NO RES
postcontent: Here's a rather scarce and very interesting WWII Colt 1911A1. This pistol started life as a commercial "Government Model" but due to the need for military arms was one of a small group transferred to a military contract and reworked to military configuration. The original commercial serial number was crudely removed by peening (both on the frame and on the slide) and a military serial number stamped over it. The pistols also received standard military proofing including the inspector's initials (G.H.D.), the "P" proofs, and the ordnance crossed cannons. The frames were also stamped with "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" and the military designation "M1911A1 U.S. ARMY". It is interesting to note that slide retained the standard commercial markings and the Colt commercial "VP" proof is still found on the left side of the trigger guard. Most of the commercial pistols of this period were fitted with the Swartz firing pin safety and these non-military components were removed, leaving empty the small milled out areas in the top of the frame and underside of the slide. Lastly, the pistols were refinished in the standard military parkerized type finish and fitted with the military style grips. All these things together make for a very unique variation of the 1911A1 pistol.This pistol is in good overall original condition. The frame and slide are serial numbered to match. The parkerized finish does show holster & handling wear with general thinning to the sharp edges and top of slide. There is no significant pitting however there is a ding to the right side of the rear sight. The barrel is interesting in that it is properly marked "COLT .45 AUTO" beneath the chamber but has no other markings, commercial or military. The barrel is finished dulite blue but polished in the white over the chamber area. The grips are in good condition, with normal wear, but no cracks. This pistol appears to be in perfect mechanical condition and everything functions properly. The bore however is rough and although there is some strong rifling remaining, it exhibits some pitting throughout. title: For Sale:  COLT  1911A1 U.S. ARMY Scarce COMMERCIAL/MILITARY...Mfd 1942, C&R
postcontent: Here's a rather scarce and very interesting WWII Colt 1911A1. This pistol started life as a commercial "Government Model" but due to the need for military arms was one of a small group transferred to a military contract and reworked to military configuration. The original commercial serial number was crudely removed by peening (both on the frame and on the slide) and a military serial number stamped over it. The pistols also received standard military proofing including the inspector's initials (G.H.D.), the "P" proofs, and the ordnance crossed cannons. The frames were also stamped with "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" and the military designation "M1911A1 U.S. ARMY". It is interesting to note that slide retained the standard commercial markings and the Colt commercial "VP" proof is still found on the left side of the trigger guard. Most of the commercial pistols of this period were fitted with the Swartz firing pin safety and these non-military components were removed, leaving empty the small milled out areas in the top of the frame and underside of the slide. Lastly, the pistols were refinished in the standard military parkerized type finish and fitted with the military style grips. All these things together make for a very unique variation of the 1911A1 pistol.This pistol is in good overall original condition. The frame and slide are serial numbered to match. The parkerized finish does show holster & handling wear with general thinning to the sharp edges and top of slide. There is no significant pitting however there is a ding to the right side of the rear sight. The barrel is interesting in that it is properly marked "COLT .45 AUTO" beneath the chamber but has no other markings, commercial or military. The barrel is finished dulite blue but polished in the white over the chamber area. The grips are in good condition, with normal wear, but no cracks. This pistol appears to be in perfect mechanical condition and everything functions properly. The bore however is rough and although there is some strong rifling remaining, it exhibits some pitting throughout. It comes with a war-time military contract magazine which shows some moderate corrosion along the sides.
